The Ultimate Miniforge Setup Guide
Phase 1: Clean Installation

This installs Miniforge entirely in your user space, providing both conda and the much faster mamba solver.

1. Download and Run the Installer:
Bash

wget "https://github.com/conda-forge/miniforge/releases/latest/download/Miniforge3-Linux-x86_64.sh"
bash Miniforge3-Linux-x86_64.sh

2. Navigate the Prompts:

    Press Enter to read the license, or q to skip.

    Type yes to accept.

    Press Enter to accept the default installation path (~/miniforge3).

Phase 2: Initialization (init)

Initialization is what allows your terminal to recognize the mamba and conda commands. It does this by injecting a small script into your shell configuration file (like ~/.bashrc or ~/.zshrc).

1. The Automated Way:
At the very end of the installation script, it will ask:

    Do you wish the installer to initialize Miniforge3 by running conda init?

Type yes.

2. The Manual Way (If you skipped it or it broke):
If your terminal says mamba: command not found after restarting, you need to initialize it manually. Run the executable directly from its installed location:
Bash

# For Bash users:
~/miniforge3/bin/conda init bash

# For Zsh users:
~/miniforge3/bin/conda init zsh

Zsh steup
While you are still sitting at that (base) void@void:/run/host/home/void$ prompt, run this instead:
conda init fish
exit
source ~/.config/fish/config.fish

If mamba activate <env-name> still give error, run this
mamba shell init --shell fish --root-prefix /home/void/miniforge3

Then, reload your Fish shell to apply the changes:
Bash

source ~/.config/fish/config.fish

Now you can run mamba activate threeML flawlessly!

3. Apply the Changes:
Always completely close your terminal and open a new one to apply the initialization. You should now see (base) next to your prompt.
Phase 3: Channel Priority (The Critical Step)

Astrophysics software is notorious for mixing Python wrappers with heavy C and Fortran binaries. If your package manager tries to mix binaries from the defaults channel with the conda-forge channel, the environment will break.

Miniforge sets conda-forge as the default, but you must ensure strict channel priority is enforced so it never accidentally pulls an incompatible underlying library.

1. Set the Configuration:
Run these commands in your terminal:
Bash

# Ensure conda-forge is the top priority channel
conda config --add channels conda-forge

# Enforce STRICT priority 
conda config --set channel_priority strict

2. Verify the Configuration:
Run this command to check your work:
Bash

conda config --show channel_priority

It should output: channel_priority: strict

Why "Strict" matters: If numpy exists in both defaults and conda-forge, strict priority forces Mamba to always pull the conda-forge version, even if the defaults version has a slightly newer version number. This prevents ABI (Application Binary Interface) mismatches when compiling your astronomy tools.
Phase 4: Your Daily Workflow Cheat Sheet

Now that your foundation is perfectly configured, here is how you manage your environments:

Create a new environment:
(Because conda-forge is now your strict default, you no longer need to type -c conda-forge every time).
Bash

mamba create -n my_env_name python=3.11 numpy scipy astropy

Activate an environment:
Bash

mamba activate my_env_name

Deactivate an environment (returns you to base):
Bash

mamba deactivate

List all your environments:
Bash

mamba env list

Delete a broken environment:
Bash

mamba env remove -n my_env_name
